segments.text: My entire life, in all its rich and complex Canadian splendor, evaporating into nothingness.
Probably still sitting in that restaurant, waiting for my return.
I think you're going to take it from me.
Just as I am, as much as you.
Burn, burn, burn, burn, burn, burn, burn, burn, burn, burn, burn, burn, burn, burn, burn, burn, burn.
Opening my eyes, I am once again standing in the Niels' front room, still mid-exorcism.
The Niels still wearing their little crucifix hats, our faces lit by the diminishing flames.
The Niels look at me desperately for reassurance, like a pair of vomity dogs.
The ceiling churning into a whirlpool of smoke.
I run upstairs to my suitcase, pop the secret compartment, retrieve my Glock 37, then run back downstairs, my head aching with false memories.
Had that entire hallucination been compressed into just a couple of minutes?
I yell, gun aloft. Every bullet in the magazine is laser engraved with the entire text of the King James Bible.
Oh, and be aware, this ghost.
It can conjure incredibly convoluted plot twists.
It really has very, very little respect for our time and intelligence.
So, uh, just stay sharp. Yeah.
The Niels return to their chanting.
Immediately, the flame turns blue, the walls dissolving into black ash.
The room fills with bloody howls, like an elephant in a car crusher.
It's weakening. I can feel it!
Soon it's gonna be forced to materialize.
We just have to remember who we are and what the point is, okay?
And fYI, the point is shooting a ghost in the face, okay?
That is the only purpose for any of this.
That's the only closure we care about.
So if you start to feel like the story is drifting away from that,
you start to feel like you're...
or learning some kind of hacky emotional lesson about how to be in the world.
You just need to reject it, okay? Reject it.
That heartfelt epiphany brewing inside you, it's just the ghost trying to subvert the plot.
You've got to swiftly and decisively undercut that bullshit before it takes over completely.
Just remember who you are, Neil.
Remember that you don't deserve a happy ending.
A scream rips a hole in the wall beside me.
A shadowy creature rushing forward, arms outstretched.
The creature skitters over a coffee table and crashes to the floor.
End simulation, says Professor Feudalburg, stepping out of the wall.
The living room vanishes, and the three of us are once again standing on the holodeck of the Balthazar.
Nice shooting, Carter, but next time I get to be the exorcist.

and room, beside which 30 little orange men applaud my words. Congratulations, says Willy Wonka, swivelling his chair towards us. That was the final test. It was all a test, dear boy. No, no, no, no, no, no.
A little bit of Hanukkah in my life, a little bit of Erica by myself, a little bit of Rita's all I need, a little bit of Tina's all I need.
